1Ô∏è‚É£ What Is a Brute-Force Attack?

A brute-force attack is an automated attempt to gain unauthorized access by systematically trying:

Large numbers of passwords

Common password lists (dictionary attacks)

Username‚Äìpassword combinations leaked from previous breaches

Attackers use tools and scripts to make thousands of login attempts per minute.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Why Weak Passwords Are Dangerous
Characteristics of Weak Passwords

Short length (e.g., 123456, admin123)

Common words or patterns

Reused across multiple websites

No complexity (no symbols, uppercase, numbers)

Real-World Reality

Most users:

Reuse passwords

Choose predictable patterns

Ignore password hygiene

This makes brute-force and credential-stuffing attacks highly effective.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Role of Missing Rate Limiting
What Is Rate Limiting?

Rate limiting restricts:

Number of login attempts per IP

Number of attempts per account

Speed of requests over time

What Happens Without It?

Unlimited login attempts

Attack scripts can try millions of combinations

No alerts or blocking

Example Scenario
Login attempts allowed: Unlimited
Result: Password cracked in minutes


Without rate limiting, the system unintentionally helps the attacker.

4Ô∏è‚É£ What You Observed During Simulation

During your simulation, you likely noticed:

‚úî Login attempts were not blocked
‚úî No CAPTCHA after multiple failures
‚úî No account lockout
‚úî No alerting or logging
‚úî Eventually, correct credentials succeeded

This demonstrates how defensive controls matter more than just encryption.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Real-World Impact of Brute-Force Attacks
Consequences

Account takeover (email, banking, CRM)

Data theft (PII, financial data)

Privilege escalation

Reputation damage

Compliance violations

Famous Attack Types

Brute-force

Dictionary attack

Credential stuffing

Most breaches today start with stolen or guessed credentials.

